  "text": "drastically suppressed variation at the conserved positions due to their functional importance. However, conservation scores are frequently plagued by an unsatisfactory number of false positives. In response, [CITATION_1] developed an elegant hybrid conservation/protein design algorithm to tease out functional from structural conserved positions. The method uses all-atom protein design [CITATION_2] [CITATION_3] to identify structurally important sites that were subsequently removed from the list of possible functional sites. This approach is quite elegant, but is limited by computational expense and the need, of course, for a structural template. Similar studies have used a variety of biophysical calculations in the same manner ( [CITATION_4] [CITATION_5] . Below, we present an analogous method to filter out putative false positives, but do so in a way that drastically reduces computational complexity and eliminates the dependence upon solved structures.",
